quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to set the height of the paragraph with the id="demo" to 68px.
[!raw!]
$("{0}").{1}({2});

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Dimensions[/h1]

The [b]width()[/b] and [b]height()[/b] methods can be used to get and set the width and height of HTML elements.

Let's set both the width and height of a div to 100px, as well as set a background color for it: [code format="js" codeId="1120"]$("div").css("background-color", "red");
$("div").width(100);
$("div").height(100);[/code]

quizzes.question:
What is the output of this code?
<div style="width:200px"></div>
<script>
$(function() {
  $("div").css("padding", "5px");
  alert($("div").innerWidth());
});
</script>

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Dimensions[/h1]

The [b]width[/b]() and [b]height[/b]() methods get and set the dimensions without the padding, borders and margins.
The [b]innerWidth[/b]() and [b]innerHeight[/b]() methods also include the padding.
The [b]outerWidth[/b]() and [b]outerHeight[/b]() methods include the padding and borders.
Check out this image to understand how they work:[img id="3120" width="100%"] 
The following example demonstrates how the methods work:
[b]HTML[/b]:[code format="html" ]<div></div>[/code]
[b]CSS[/b]: [code format="css" ]div {
  width: 300px;
  height: 100px;
  padding: 10px;
  margin: 20px;
  border: 3px solid blue;
  background-color: red;
  color: white;
}[/code]
[b]JS[/b]: [code format="js" codeId="1121"]$(function() {
  var txt = "";
  txt += "width: " + $("div").width() + " ";
  txt += "height: " + $("div").height() + "<br/>";
  txt += "innerWidth: " + $("div").innerWidth() + "  ";
  txt += "innerHeight: " + $("div").innerHeight() + "<br/>";
  txt += "outerWidth: " + $("div").outerWidth() + "  ";
  txt += "outerHeight: " + $("div").outerHeight();
    
  $("div").html(txt);
});[/code]
[note]Run the code to see the values returned by the dimension methods.[/note]
